{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ceff1545-8ee0-45c2-8761-639a0b9687a7","content":"With MSTest 3.8+ on .NET 9, here's the recommended pattern using constructor injection for `TestContext` combined with `IAsyncInitialization`:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization\n{\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    // Synchronous initialization via constructor injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        // Sync setup here (e.g., create objects, set config)\n    }\n\n    // Asynchronous initialization\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // Async setup here (e.g., DB connections, HTTP clients)\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void SyncTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext);\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task AsyncTest()\n    {\n        await Task.Delay(1);\n        Assert.IsNotNull(TestContext.TestRunDirectory);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** — MSTest 3.x injects `TestContext` automatically via the constructor parameter (no need for the property setter pattern).\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** — implement this interface for async setup that runs after construction but before each test.\n- The older `[TestInitialize]` / `[ClassInitialize]` attributes still work but constructor injection is the modern idiomatic approach.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"da88594f-a5b2-4976-bb5b-88600c774906","outputTokens":357,"requestId":"8431:37AAD:21093A6:2493535:6A0AD2C9"},"id":"7f56018e-f664-4680-b9ac-434a71699674","timestamp":"2026-05-18T08:50:26.099Z","parentId":"91c61d6f-2e5e-4ba2-8167-17b3e86d5b58"}
